ists, procurators, newspaper reporters, and some penal administrators to rally around the slogan "The camp is not a resort" and succeeded in reimposing harsher conditions for inmates. By the mid-1960s the Soviet Gulag had emerged as a hybrid system forged from the old Stalinist system, the vision promoted by Khrushchev and others in the mid-1950s, and the ensuing counterreform movement. This new penal equilibrium largely persisted until the fall of the Soviet Union.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aConcentration campszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aInternment campszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPrisonszSoviet UnionxHistory. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170604240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501706042423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501706042/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles